---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Masthead from '../components/Masthead.astro';
import SiteFooter from '../components/SiteFooter.astro';
---
<Base
  title="About Tipsheet"
  description="Tipsheet extracts the signal from the noise of Indian equities. We turn dense, consequential exchange filings into sharp, uncompromising editorial intelligence."
>
  <Masthead />
  <main>
    <article class="prose-page">
      <header>
        <div class="kicker"><span>About</span></div>
        <h1 class="page-title">The signal in the noise of Indian equities.</h1>
      </header>

      <hr class="rule" />

      <h2>The Information Deficit</h2>
      <p>
        The Indian equity market generates thousands of regulatory disclosures a week. Most of it is noise. But buried in that noise are the structural shifts, the governance breaks, and the capital moves that dictate market reality.
      </p>
      <p>
        Historically, investors had two choices: wade through raw, unformatted PDF filings, or rely on financial media that pads routine updates with manufactured drama and syndicated wire copy. Neither respects the reader’s time. We built Tipsheet to offer a third way.
      </p>

      <h2>Our Standard</h2>
      <p>
        Tipsheet is an unapologetic, high-fidelity editorial filter. We read every material disclosure filed with the Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) and National Stock Exchange (NSE). We strip away the corporate boilerplate, extract the consequential math, and publish a razor-sharp editorial note. 
      </p>
      <p>
        Our tone is anchored in the tradition of the FT’s <em>Lex</em> column and the WSJ’s <em>Heard on the Street</em>: brief, analytical, and entirely grounded in primary evidence. If we cannot verify a claim directly from an exchange filing, we delete it.
      </p>

      <h2>The Architecture</h2>
      <p>
        We operate at the bleeding edge of editorial technology. Tipsheet is powered by a proprietary computational pipeline that ingests raw exchange data, scores it for materiality, and synthesizes the core facts using large language models. 
      </p>
      <p>
        However, technology is merely our engine; editorial judgment is our steering wheel. Every output is governed by an unyielding set of journalistic constraints. The AI does not predict prices, it does not invent context, and it does not write clickbait. To understand the exact mechanics of this hybrid intelligence model, review our <a href="/methodology/">Methodology</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>What We Do Not Do</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>No noise:</strong> We do not aggregate other journalists' work or republish wire copy.</li>
        <li><strong>No advice:</strong> We do not issue "buy, sell, or hold" recommendations.</li>
        <li><strong>No compromise:</strong> We do not run advertising, sponsored placements, or advertorials.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="team">Independence & Ownership</h2>
      <p>
        Tipsheet is funded independently and operates entirely free of external editorial pressure. Our mandate is singular: to serve the reader with clarity and precision. 
      </p>

      <h2>The Archive</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/filings/">The Wire</a> — The complete chronological record of our filings coverage.</li>
        <li><a href="/companies/">Company Intelligence</a> — The editorial ledger for every listed entity we track.</li>
        <li><a href="/markets/">Market Telemetry</a> — A live pulse of Indian indices, FX, and macro conditions.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Contact</h2>
      <p>
        For inquiries, corrections, or cryptographic keys, see our <a href="/contact/">Contact</a> page. We hold ourselves accountable to strict <a href="/editorial-standards/">Editorial Standards</a> and a transparent <a href="/corrections/">Corrections Policy</a>.
      </p>
    </article>
  </main>
  <SiteFooter />
</Base>
